\begin_layout Title
CS240: Homework 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Sahit Mandala
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the original statement has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $A\Longrightarrow(B\vee C)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
a)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
i) 
\begin_inset Formula $B\vee C\Longrightarrow A$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
ii) Converse 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
iii) Not equivalent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
vi) Notice that when 
\begin_inset Formula $B=T,C=T,A=F$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(A\Longrightarrow(B\vee C))\equiv(F\Longrightarrow(T\vee T))\equiv F\Longrightarrow T\equiv T$
\end_inset

 but
\begin_inset Formula $((B\vee C)\Longrightarrow A)\equiv((T\vee T)\Longrightarrow F)\equiv F$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $((B\vee C)\Longrightarrow A)\not\equiv A\Longrightarrow B\vee C$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
b) 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
i) 
\begin_inset Formula $(\neg B\vee\neg C)\Longrightarrow\neg A$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
ii) Neither 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
iii) Not equivalent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
vi) Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $A=T,B=T,C=F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\neg B\vee\neg C)\Longrightarrow\neg A\equiv(\neg T\vee\neg F)\Longrightarrow\neg T\equiv T\Longrightarrow F\equiv F$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $A\Longrightarrow(B\vee C)\equiv T\Longrightarrow T\vee F\equiv T\Longrightarrow T\equiv T$
\end_inset

.
 Because the 2 expressions do not agree on the same propsitional values,
 
\begin_inset Formula $A\Longrightarrow(B\vee C)\not\equiv(\neg B\vee\neg C)\Longrightarrow\neg A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
c) 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
i) 
\begin_inset Formula $A\wedge\neg B\wedge\neg C$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
ii) Neither 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
iii) Not equivalent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
vi) Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A=F,B=T,C=T$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\wedge\neg B\wedge\neg C\equiv F\wedge\neg T\wedge\neg T\equiv F$
\end_inset

 But
\begin_inset Formula $A\Longrightarrow(B\vee C)\equiv F\Longrightarrow(T\vee T)\equiv F\Longrightarrow T\equiv T$
\end_inset

.
 Because the 2 expressions do not agree on the same propsitional values,
 
\begin_inset Formula $A\Longrightarrow(B\vee C)\not\equiv A\wedge\neg B\wedge\neg C$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
d) 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
i) 
\begin_inset Formula $(\neg B\wedge\neg C)\Longrightarrow\neg A$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
ii) Contrapositive, noting that by deMorgan's law, 
\begin_inset Formula $(\neg B\wedge\neg C)\equiv\neg(B\vee C)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
iii) Equivalent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
vi) Here, we construct the truth table and show the equivalence of the 2
 expression across all propositional values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula $\begin{array}{ccccc}
A & B & C & A\Longrightarrow(B\vee C) & (\neg B\wedge\neg C)\Longrightarrow\neg A\\
T & T & T & T & T\\
T & T & F & T & T\\
T & F & T & T & T\\
T & F & F & F & F\\
F & T & T & T & T\\
F & T & F & T & T\\
F & F & T & T & T\\
F & F & F & T & T
\end{array}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
e) 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
i) 
\begin_inset Formula $(A\wedge\neg C)\Longrightarrow B$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
ii) Neither 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
iii) Equivalent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
vi) Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\Longrightarrow B\equiv\neg A\vee B$
\end_inset

.
 Then using associativity and commutivity on 
\begin_inset Formula $\vee$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $A\Longrightarrow(B\vee C)\equiv\neg A\vee(B\vee C)\equiv(\neg A\vee C)\vee B$
\end_inset

.
 Using deMorgan's law, 
\begin_inset Formula $(\neg A\vee C)\vee B\equiv\neg(A\wedge\neg C)\vee B\equiv(A\wedge\neg C)\Longrightarrow B$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, we have shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $(A\wedge\neg C)\Longrightarrow B\equiv A\Longrightarrow(B\vee C)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Section*
Problem 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
a)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, we construct the truth table:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\begin{array}{ccc}
P & Q & P\wedge(Q\vee P)\\
T & T & T\\
T & F & T\\
F & T & F\\
F & F & F
\end{array}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that P and 
\begin_inset Formula $P\wedge(Q\vee P)$
\end_inset

 are equivalent on every permutation of propositional values, despite the
 value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $P\wedge(Q\vee P)\equiv P$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
b)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $(P\Longrightarrow Q)\wedge(P\Longrightarrow\neg Q)\equiv\neg P$
\end_inset

.
 To prove this, we shall use a truth table:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\begin{array}{cccc}
P & Q & (P\Longrightarrow Q)\wedge(P\Longrightarrow\neg Q) & \neg P\\
T & T & T\wedge F\equiv F & F\\
T & F & F\wedge T\equiv F & F\\
F & T & T\wedge T\equiv T & T\\
F & F & T\wedge T\equiv T & T
\end{array}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we can see, 
\begin_inset Formula $(P\Longrightarrow Q)\wedge(P\Longrightarrow\neg Q)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg P$
\end_inset

 are equal across all propostional values, so 
\begin_inset Formula $(P\Longrightarrow Q)\wedge(P\Longrightarrow\neg Q)\equiv\neg P$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
c)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\Longrightarrow B\equiv\neg A\vee B$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $(P\Longrightarrow Q)\Longrightarrow(P\Longrightarrow R)\equiv(\neg P\vee Q)\Longrightarrow(\neg P\vee R)\equiv\neg(\neg P\vee Q)\vee(\neg P\vee R)$
\end_inset

.
 By deMorgan's law, 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg(\neg P\vee Q)\vee(\neg P\vee R)\equiv(P\wedge\neg Q)\vee(\neg P\vee R)\equiv((P\wedge\neg Q)\vee\neg P)\vee R$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $(P\wedge\neg Q)\vee\neg P\equiv(P\vee\neg P)\wedge(\neg P\vee\neg Q)\equiv T\wedge(\neg P\vee\neg Q)\equiv(\neg P\vee\neg Q)\equiv\neg(P\wedge Q)$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $((P\wedge\neg Q)\vee\neg P)\vee R\equiv\neg(P\wedge Q)\vee R\equiv(P\wedge Q)\Longrightarrow R$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $(P\Longrightarrow Q)\Longrightarrow(P\Longrightarrow R)\equiv(P\wedge Q)\Longrightarrow R$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
a)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\exists x\in D\,[P(x)\wedge\neg H(x)]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
b)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\forall x\in D\,[(P(x)\wedge H(x))\Longrightarrow\neg I(x)]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
c)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\forall x\in D\,[I(x)\Longrightarrow(P(x)\vee R(x))]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
d)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\forall x\in D\,[\neg K(Darby,x)\Longrightarrow\neg T(Darby,x)]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
e)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\exists x\in D\,(R(x)\wedge(\forall y\in D\,[I(y)\implies K(x,y)])$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
f)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some politicians are honest, but not all people are politicians and are
 honest
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
g)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Everyone trusts every honest politician.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
h)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If Jessie is honest, then there are some influence-peddlers that Jessie
 trusts 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
i)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is not someone who trusts everyone.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
j)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Everyone who is a registered lobbyist has someone other than themselves
 that they trust
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\neg(\forall x\in Z)(\exists y\in Z)((x+y=0)\wedge(y<x))\equiv$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists x\in Z)\neg(\exists y\in Z)((x+y=0)\wedge(y<x))\equiv$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists x\in Z)(\forall y\in Z)\neg((x+y=0)\wedge(y<x))\equiv$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists x\in Z)(\forall y\in Z)(\neg(x+y=0)\vee\neg(y<x))\equiv$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists x\in Z)(\forall y\in Z)((x+y\not=0)\vee(y\geq x))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Problem 5
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Set A as Alex's decision, B as Blair's, C as Casey's decision.
 Then we assume the following are all true:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If Alex orders dessert, so does Casey: 
\begin_inset Formula $A\Longrightarrow C$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Either Casey or Blair always orders dessert but never both at the same meal:
 
\begin_inset Formula $B\oplus C\equiv(B\vee C)\wedge\neg(B\wedge C)$
\end_inset

 (that is, XOR)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Either Alex or Blair or both order dessert: 
\begin_inset Formula $A\vee B$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If Blair orders dessert, so does Alex: 
\begin_inset Formula $B\Longrightarrow A$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Constructing the truth table:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\begin{array}{ccccccc}
A & B & C & A\Longrightarrow C & B\oplus C & A\vee B & B\Longrightarrow A\\
T & T & T & T & F & T & T\\
T & T & F & F & T & T & T\\
T & F & T & T & T & T & T\\
T & F & F & F & F & T & T\\
F & T & T & T & F & T & F\\
F & T & F & T & T & T & F\\
F & F & T & T & T & F & T\\
F & F & F & T & F & F & T
\end{array}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The only set of values on the variables which satisfies our assumption that
 the given propositions are all true are 
\begin_inset Formula $A=T,B=F,C=T$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is, Alex and Casey get dessert while Blair does not.
\end_layout

